<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="417" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1264,2042]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1586,1612]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">Distribution.</emphasis>
Off 
<collectingCountry box="[408,471,1586,1612]" name="Chile" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">Chile</collectingCountry>
, from 
<geoCoordinate box="[547,622,1586,1613]" degrees="34.5" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" precision="5555" value="-34.5">34.5°S</geoCoordinate>
to the Magellan Strait and Beagle Channel, South Orkney, South Shetland, Kerguelen and Crozet Islands and 
<collectingCountry box="[606,760,1622,1649]" name="New Zealand" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, 
<quantity box="[772,903,1622,1649]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.49" metricValueMax="12.1" metricValueMin="0.88" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" unit="m" value="649.0" valueMax="1210.0" valueMin="88.0">88–1210 m</quantity>
. The present report near 
<collectingCountry box="[1186,1337,1622,1649]" name="New Zealand" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwabe &amp; Sellanes" authorityYear="2010" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="laurae">
<emphasis box="[1377,1393,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">L</emphasis>
. cf. 
<emphasis box="[151,224,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">laurae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would greatly extend the previously known distribution of this species if confirmed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="417" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1264,2042]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1694,1720]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">Remarks.</emphasis>
The examined specimen (NMNZ M 051009, with BL 11.0 mm) has 11 gills per side arranged from valve VI to anus, and a 3.0 mm long radula with 30 transverse rows of mature teeth. The 
<collectingCountry box="[1184,1335,1729,1756]" name="New Zealand" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
material shows some differences to the 
<typeStatus box="[497,595,1765,1791]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">holotype</typeStatus>
and to some specimens studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sirenko, B. I." box="[994,1164,1765,1792]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref19002" refString="Sirenko, B. I. (2015) Shallow and deep-sea chitons of the genus Leptochiton Gray, 1847 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora: Lepidopleurida) from Peruvian and Chilean waters. Zootaxa, 4033 (2), 151 - 202. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4033.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Sirenko (2015)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Sirenko, B. I. &amp; Sellanes, J." pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="259 - 279" refId="ref19195" refString="Sirenko, B. I. &amp; Sellanes, J. (2016) Update of the genus Leptochiton (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in Chilean deep waters: three new reports and description of two new species. Zootaxa, 4173 (3), 259 - 279. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4173.3.5" type="journal article" year="2016">Sirenko &amp; Sellanes (2016)</bibRefCitation>
. The examined specimen differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[701,799,1801,1827]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">holotype</typeStatus>
by having 1 or 2 ribs on dorsal scales [vs. 6–8 very faint longitudinal ribs in the 
<typeStatus box="[413,511,1836,1862]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schwabe, E. &amp; Sellanes, J." box="[526,828,1836,1863]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="31 - 55" refId="ref18862" refString="Schwabe, E. &amp; Sellanes, J. (2010) Revision of Chilean bathyal chitons Mollusca: Polyplacophora) associated with cold-seeps, including description of a new species of Leptochiton (Leptochitonidae). Organisms Diversity &amp; Evolution, 10 (1), 31 - 55. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13127 - 009 - 0002 - 6" type="journal article" year="2010">Schwabe &amp; Sellanes 2010</bibRefCitation>
)]. In my opinion the number of ribs on dorsal scales is variable in this species. Specimens from South Shetland Islands were shown (
<bibRefCitation author="Sirenko, B. I." box="[1018,1171,1872,1899]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref19002" refString="Sirenko, B. I. (2015) Shallow and deep-sea chitons of the genus Leptochiton Gray, 1847 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora: Lepidopleurida) from Peruvian and Chilean waters. Zootaxa, 4033 (2), 151 - 202. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4033.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Sirenko 2015</bibRefCitation>
) to have smooth scales, while those from 
<collectingCountry box="[346,496,1908,1935]" name="New Zealand" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and the Magellan region have 1–2 ribs and the specimens from Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1316,1377,1908,1934]" name="Chile" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">Chile</collectingCountry>
have 3 ribs. Compared to the previously studied material, the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[968,1118,1944,1970]" name="New Zealand" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
have a longer antemucronal area and rounded valves. As was mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sirenko, B. I." box="[683,852,1979,2006]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="151 - 202" refId="ref19002" refString="Sirenko, B. I. (2015) Shallow and deep-sea chitons of the genus Leptochiton Gray, 1847 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora: Lepidopleurida) from Peruvian and Chilean waters. Zootaxa, 4033 (2), 151 - 202. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4033.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Sirenko (2015)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Sirenko, B. I. &amp; Sellanes, J." box="[906,1204,1979,2006]" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" pagination="259 - 279" refId="ref19195" refString="Sirenko, B. I. &amp; Sellanes, J. (2016) Update of the genus Leptochiton (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) in Chilean deep waters: three new reports and description of two new species. Zootaxa, 4173 (3), 259 - 279. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4173.3.5" type="journal article" year="2016">Sirenko &amp; Sellanes (2016)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schwabe &amp; Sellanes" authorityYear="2010" box="[1211,1313,1979,2005]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="laurae">
<emphasis box="[1211,1313,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">L. laurae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the group of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sowerby III" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[295,392,2015,2041]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Leptochitonidae" genus="Leptochiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidopleurida" pageId="16" pageNumber="417" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sykesi">
<emphasis box="[295,392,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="417">L. sykesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
